posts.name: raj
posts.cooked: Hey guys! I hope all of y’all’s builds are going well as we get closer to competitions! Our team has been experimenting with a few protective measures to prevent coral from getting stuck inside our robot and damaging electronics and mechanisms at the base of our robot. At the back of our robot, we are planning on pulling a 1323 and making a very big box since we have nothing leaving the frame perimeter on that side, but are having more issues with the front on our scoring and elevator side. We’ve tried some setups with fabric and polycarbonate and haven’t had much success. What are ways that teams are preventing coral from falling into their robot, especially beneath an elevator when it is extended? Any help or ideas would be appreciated. Thanks!

posts.name: Billfred Leverette (he/him/not Bill)
posts.cooked:
Suppdog222:

What are some ways teams protect exposed wires that can’t be covered by a lexan panel?

I’m not particularly concerned about bare wire.  I’ll zip tie it using cheap mounts and cable ties for strain relief and neatness, but that’s about it.  (Wipe the spot down with an alcohol wipe right before and let it dry, it’ll do wonders for adhesion.)

For things that might crack or get bumped like in that 111 video, I’m planning a mix of foam floor tiles or 3D printing guards out of TPU to absorb the whack.

Or, if the lexan poses a cost issue rather than an engineering issue, corrugated plastic (think yard sign material) will get you a lot of the way at a very nice price.

Garrison:

Something like this plastic split wire loom/conduit

Cheaper from Harbor Freight , if one is nearby.  You can also use the igus energy chain that’s been in past kits of parts; if you don’t have it around, other teams nearby might.  Or use your Automation Direct voucher on some of their energy chain .

posts.cooked: Hi! Our robot currently has a total of 4 panels: Front electronics panel, two side panels, and one rear panel. The most tested one is the front electronics panel as falling coral from L4 as it is regularly struck. From testing, other panels haven’t been hit yet but we feel it is a necessary precaution. Despite the “overprotection”, the coral has gone into the box of a bot through the bottom of the extended elevator twice. We are seeing if we can make a net from surgical tubing from the chassis to the bottom of the first stage that extends with the elevator.
